                                    <note xml:lang="en"><p>Karl Julius Reinhart Hoerning (1855–1937) was born in in Meiningen, Thuringia. He entered the University of Leipzig in 1874 at the age of 18, initially to study theology and oriental languages. However, his focus soon shifted exclusively to oriental languages. He studied various languages, including Sanskrit, Arabic, Persian, Turkish, Syriac, Ethiopic, and Rabbinic Hebrew under different professors. The turning point came when Friedrich Delitzsch began Assyriology lectures in the summer semester of 1875, and Hoerning, captivated by the subject, decided to specialize in this new field. 
<lb/> In 1879 he was appointed assistant to the Keeper of Oriental Manuscripts, Charles Pierre Henri Rieu (1820–1902), at the British Museum, London. His handwritten descriptions of the (mostly) Qaraite manuscripts from the Shapira Collection (today held at the British Library) served as the basis for subsequent catalogs, especially the Catalogue of the Hebrew and Samaritan manuscripts in the British Museum by G. Margoliouth. </p><p> Literature: 
<lb/> Karl Julius Reinhart Hoerning, “Das sechsseitige Prisma des Sanherib in transcribirtem Grundtext und Uebersetzung nebst Beiträgen zu seiner Erklärung” (Inaugural dissertation, University of Leipzig, 1878). 
<lb/> Benjamin Richler, “Hoerning, Reinhardt,” in his Guide to Hebrew Manuscript Collections, 2nd ed. (Jerusalem: The Israel Academy of Sciences and Humanities, 2014), p. 96. 
<lb/></p></note>
                                    <persName>Karl Julius Reinhart Hoerning </persName>
                                    <quote xml:lang="en"><p>Fragment of a Commentary on Leviticus, ch. Xi. with translation, probably by ar-Ra’is Abu Sa’id. XIIth or XIII th cent. .</p><p>A Commentary on Numbers, ch. xxv 10- xxx 1, with translation, by ar-Ra’is Aub Sa’id, imperfect at the end, of the same age.</p><p>Fragment of a Commentary on Deuteronomy, ch. xxviii; of the XIIth or XIIIth cent.</p><p>An interpretation of Job, ch. xxxvi 12-33; xxxvii 22- xxxviii 34; probably of the XIVth cent.</p><p>Fragment of a Hebrew Grammar; probably of  the XIth cent. Arabic.</p><p>Paper, ff. 111. Sm. 8o.
<lb/></p></quote>
                                    <bibl>
